4.99/5  rDev +7.3%look: 4.75 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5I consider myself a relative newcomer to the world of craft beer, having gotten into it rather late in life. However, I consider myself a quick learner. I have been rating and reviewing beers on BA for a little more than a year now. I feel that day by day I'm acquiring more beer tasting experience and that my reviews are getting better. As a result of an increasingly discerning and sophisticated palate, I find that my reviews while mostly positive, are becoming less effusive in praise. This past spring, my father, after a trip from San Francisco, brought me at my request a few bottles of Pliny the Elder. Long story short, I thought it was quite possibly the tastiest and most perfectly balanced IPA I had ever had. I had no choice but to give it a perfect 5.
 Fast forward to Columbus day weekend of 2015. My wife and I drove up from NYC for a weekend getaway at a bed and breakfast we like in Lake Luzerne NY. On a whim, from there we decided to drive up to Vermont for a day. We got to Burlington and I immediately went in search of the famous and elusive Heady Topper. After asking around, I found out that it sold out at the liquor stores, but was available at several bars and restaurants on Church Street. We went to have dinner at the Scuffer, which is where I finally laid my lips on this white whale. The verdict:
Absolutely fucking delicious!!!! The aroma is dank, piny, resiny and overpowering with hops, yet, there is also a strong biscuity and crockery malt. The taste: total hop bomb yet such a strong sweet malt presence. Truly a perfect balance. What a tasty, flavorful and delicious brew. So easily drinkable. If I wasn't driving, I would have had about 5 of them. 
 As for my final score, Ive debated whether or not to give it a perfect 5. I believe that this brew is as good or even better than Pliny the elder. However, as was strongly suggested by the can and my server, I decided to heed their advice of keeping it in the can. However, my wife wanted a taste but refused to drink it from the can. (I know...she's weird about this, but hey, we all have our little quirks) Anyway, I poured her a little bit in a glass and could tell that it was an attractive hazy looking brew .I also took a sip from the glass and could tell how the taste opened up. I could also see how in the can, the tastes of the hops felt more compact and intense, which I might like better. So there you have it. This beer is like a perfect 5, except for the fact that since most of it was invisible to me inside of the can, I was not able to properly evaluate it on the look. 2,578 charactersGajo74, Oct 13, 2015
