3.98/5  rDev -14.4%look: 2.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 3.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.25Before I go further with this review let me make two caveats:  First, the three times I received a can of this brew was from people who traveled to get it, so I don't know how it was kept for the days or weeks before it got to me.  Second, I'm not trying to topple a giant, Just trying to give an honest review while trying to follow BJCP guidelines and not let public hype influence my observations...  Anywho, let's drink some Heady Topper!!!  
From the Can (Only three days old according to the friend who got it), drunk from 40-50 F
Even though it says "Drink From The Can" I poured about 4oz into a juice glass to evaluate: 1.5 fingers of lasting white head with medium/small bubbles on top of a golden yellow body with slight orange/light-copper highlights.  BJCP says Imperial/American IPA's can be "a bit" hazy...  This brew's more cloudy than a Hefe... sorry Alchemist, points off there if we're going by the book...
Aroma Is pleasant, huge mix of hop florals (citrus, piney) with hints of malt, light brown sugar, and stonefruit, but on this particular can nothing seems to stand out above the rest - it makes me think "American IPA" but not much else.   *Note, stronger aromas started to come forward as it warmed, more florals and malt sweetness
Taste is fairly balanced between malt sweetness and hop bitterness considering how hoppy it is.  Flavors of grass, lilac, other florals, light brown sugar, peach, apricot, macintosh apple, with a tinge of yeasty breadyness.
Mouthfeel is spot-on, light to medium bodied, fairly smoth with a prickle of carbonation that dries with the hop bitterness at the end, makes me want to take sip after sip.  Well done.
Overall, a well done IPA, But this can (in my opinion) rates lower than the first two I had over a month ago.  While this batch seemed to be more hop forward (the hops were definitely more aggressive in this batch) the first two I had were definitely more malt forward with larger bursts of stone fruit, ripe honey-crisp apple and tropical fruit flavors cutting through the background.  Had I rated one of those cans instead of this one, my personal bias towards more malty beers might have given it a few more points. (except for appearance, guidelines are guidelines no matter how tasty the beer is)  I thought those two were amazing and delicious, this one was just "eh, another strong, bitter American IPA"  Has anyone else found such variability in this brew?  All that aside, still my #1 East Coast IPA.  
Also, they really mean "drink from the can" the 4oz I poured out lost the more subtle hop and fruit flavors fairly quickly. 2,609 charactersKJHB, Mar 16, 2015
