4.95/5  rDev +6.5%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 5I wish my farts didn't smell so bad after drinking this gift from the gods74 charactersAdel, Jan 20, 2015
4.53/5  rDev -2.6%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.75Hopfensaft, Jan 20, 2015
4.99/5  rDev +7.3%look: 4.75 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5I drank some from the can and poured the rest to see it. 
Appearance - This is the one area that took a hit for me. it has a golden opacity that glows with light present. The head was creamy as the name would suggest. The bubbles seemed to never end
Aroma - If I could give one aspect of this beer the highest notes, it would be the nose. It was intoxicating in and of itself. The floral bouquet dances and plays with your senses, letting you know something amazing is coming. It had small traces of fruits... maybe papaya, orange... The hops were just right
Taste - The initial flavour comes through strong and clean but not overpowering like some west coast ipas. You could tell that the flavour profile has taken time to craft. There were still some fruits coming through, but I think they are mainly ester-driven: some lemon, some cantaloupe or melon. The malt shows itself with is a big split from that west coast bite
Mouthfeel - creamy carbonation, with a smooth finish. It was pleasantly dry and popped off the back of the tongue.
Overall - Yes it lived up to the hype. 1,082 charactersCraigTravor, Jan 20, 2015
4.55/5  rDev -2.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.75L - nice can, yellowish orange body, opaque, two finger head fades slowly
S - grapefruit, a sort of dry woody smell, malt, pine, floral
T - orange juice, medium sweetness, a little pine, hint of biscuit, clean tasting (no "weird" vegetal flavors, no onion, not very dank), perfectly balanced, definitely dominated by PNW rather than NZ hops, fairly bitter finish
F - medium to high carbonation, medium thickness, slight heat on the finish
O - This is an updated review after several years.  Much of what once made this beer unique has become common.  I don't think I could pick this out of a lineup of Grimm DIPAs, for example.  If anything, HT would be the most indistinct, which makes sense -- it helped to define a style, and now sits smack dab in the middle of that style. 780 characterscfalls, Jan 20, 2015
