4.17/5  rDev -10.3%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 422 oz. bottle courtesy of the generous masterhomebrewer - thanks, buddy! I wanted to consume this one as quickly as possible, so that it would be as fresh as possible (as is encouraged by the brewmaster on the excellently written label). Poured in to a large tulip.
Appearance: Pours a surprisingly dirty looking olive-hued goldenrod, much darker and hazier than I'd expected, though plenty of active carbonation is visible around the edges of the tulip. A torrent of it, actually, well distributed, and fairly slow, given the sheer quantity - normally beers that showcase this much carbonation have much more spry bubbles. It's nice, though, sort of like suspended jewels up and down the sides of the glass. The head has above average retention - average for an excellent DIPA, of course - emerging slowly to a maximum height of about a finger and change, a dull, jaundiced ecru that fades to a thick, soapy collar, a persistent and largely uniform surface dusting, and a nice amount of sticky, snowy, crisp side lacing, which successive sips only do so much to erode. The process on this one is fantastic - it's only the colors that are a knock against it. Filter this one, and I bet it's a 5.0.
Aroma: Like a baby Pliny the Elder, in many ways. That is, similar in composition, but not in strength. Sweet, juicy citrus dominates the nose, with freshly squeezed and earthy grapefruit, orange, mango, and even springy apricot notes intermingling with lots of leafy, herbal spice. Complex and concentrated.
Taste: Slightly less flavorful than the aroma would suggest. First, the malt backbone is very subdued. I only detect faint hints of roast, and very little sweetness - it's mostly a dry, water cracker-like backbone, a little husky, sort of like a dry English pale ale. This isn't in and of itself a problem, but it misses an opportunity to interact favorably with the hop notes, rather than just let them take the stage on their own. To each his or her own, perhaps.
Now, to their credit, the aforementioned hop notes are pretty stellar. Tons of east coast notes here - lots of grassy notes, freshly mowed hay, grassy and floral, second only to the spicy, herbal, leafy notes. Not a lot of pine here - slightly resinous, but more dank. The spice is distinctly herbal, tobacco-like, faintly wintergreen-like. There's also plenty of citrus, which interacts with the herbal notes to suggest earthy pith, like biting in to the fruit rather than drinking the juice. The "juice" label is further diminished by the relative dryness of the beer. The white grapefruit (not tart enough to be ruby red) and orange notes are here, as are a few other tropical fruit notes, kiwi and pineapple, definite peach, slight apricot - but they're wholesome, a little dirty, and (by virtue of the lack of sweetness) very "essence"-esque, oily.
And bitterness? Sure, it's here, but again, just like the malt backbone, it doesn't overpower the hop flavors themselves. Part of me is appreciative of this - the low (relatively) level of bitterness and the low (relatively) level of sweetness are in balance with one another. 
If I had to guess? Simcoe is definitely here, as are a few "C"s (Centennial and Columbus?), as is one of the leafier varieties (Yaikma, Amarillo, or something of the like). I'd love to see the hop schedule on this one.
Mouthfeel: Oily, and incredibly smooth and soft. The low final gravity makes for a beer that's never even close to cloying or syrupy, and the low "feel" of the carbonation (quite in contrast to what was visible initially) works well with this. The smoothness of the beer on the whole also works well with the flavor profile, amplifying the right notes while not pushing anything in your face. 
Drinkability: The best east coast DIPA I've ever had? Maybe (it's up there w/ HopSlam, which is marginally east coast, I suppose). But it's lacking in some of that bold dynamism that makes beers like PtE (and to a lesser extent PtY), Hop 15, Pure Hoppiness, and White Knuckle so fantastic. At 8.0%, it's not nearly as bold in the ethanol department as some of those, though (which is to its credit), but I would gladly accept this one at 9%, 10%, or even 11% if it could just amp up the sweetness and the bitterness a little. I know the back of the bottle says that this beer isn't aiming to be the biggest, or the strongest, or the most bitter, but the flavor combination is great enough that, with a little extra thrust, this one could be the world's best DIPA. On the whole, though, I was really impressed with this one and thrilled to try it - Heady Topper is the best non-Bell's DIPA (HopSlam, Oracle, and Big Head all top it) that I've had brewed outside California ... and that's sayin' something. 4,730 charactersCrellMoset, Dec 13, 2010
